Fig.Â 4
 shows the Global Moran's I of poverty probability at the county level from 1992 to 2013. The results reveal a strong spatial autocorrelation of the poverty probability among counties in China; all the values are over 0.7. In addition, the changes in value fluctuation are relatively small, which indicates that the distribution of poor counties and nonpoor counties in China has been highly related to the spatial distribution for many years. The relatively small changes in value fluctuation also indicate that the counties with similar development levels have prominent spatial agglomerations. The LISA maps for 1992 to 2013 have similar distribution characteristics; therefore, this paper uses 2010 as an example to investigate the local autocorrelation of the poverty probability at the county level (Fig.Â 5
). The figure shows that the high-high clusters are primarily located in Southwest China, Central China and Northwest China. East China, Southern China and Northeastern part of China are identified as low-low clusters. These results indicate that relatively poor and nonpoor counties have obvious regional distribution features.
